  <section class="legal-document">
    <div class="legal-container">
      <div class="legal-header">
        <h1>No Hello</h1>
        <p class="legal-date">Please share your question right away instead of opening with a lonely greeting.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="legal-content">
        <div class="legal-section">
          <h2>The pattern we try to avoid</h2>
          <div class="quote-block">
            <p><strong>You:</strong> Hello?</p>
            <p><strong>Teammate:</strong> <em>(now waiting, guessing what you might need)</em></p>
            <p><strong>You:</strong> Are you free? Can you jump on a call?</p>
            <p><strong>Teammate:</strong> I was focused on a deploy and had to stop to see if this was urgent.</p>
          </div>
          <p>That tiny pause between “hello” and the actual question is a productivity sink. Everyone—including the CEO—has to alt-tab away from deep work to check if they’re missing something important. Multiply that by dozens of chats a day and an entire team loses hours.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="legal-section">
          <h2>Why it hurts more than it seems</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Context switching costs time:</strong> Pulling someone out of flow for a context-free ping can take 20–30 minutes of recovery.</li>
            <li><strong>It creates social pressure:</strong> The recipient feels rude if they don’t reply immediately—even though there isn’t a question yet.</li>
            <li><strong>Leaders aren’t immune:</strong> Our CEO’s calendar is stacked. A vague greeting can derail the entire day while they wait for clarification.</li>
            <li><strong>Written records matter:</strong> Threads become impossible to search when they start with filler like “hi” or “quick question.”</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="legal-section">
          <h2>Do this instead</h2>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Lead with the ask.</strong> “Hey Mia — the billing job failed on shard 03. Can you restart it?”</li>
            <li><strong>Add relevant context.</strong> Include logs, screenshots, links, and deadlines so the reader can help asynchronously.</li>
            <li><strong>Mention urgency honestly.</strong> “Blocking launch” is clearer than “ASAP!!!” and lets people prioritize.</li>
            <li><strong>Respect availability.</strong> If you truly need a live conversation, propose times instead of demanding immediate attention.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>Sending the full message upfront is considerate and lets the other person reply when they can, without a round of “hello” / “are you there?” limbo.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="legal-section">
          <h2>When a greeting is totally fine</h2>
          <p>We’re not banning friendliness. A warm hello is perfect when it comes paired with substance, or when you’re already in a meeting, stand-up, social channel, or hallway chat. Just remember that in work chat, <strong>hello + question</strong> beats <strong>hello … (wait)</strong> every time.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="legal-section">
          <h2>FAQ</h2>
          <h3>But what if I’m not sure the person is around?</h3>
          <p>Leave the message anyway. Most tools show presence indicators. The other person will see it when they return and answer with full context.</p>
          <h3>What if the CEO likes quick pings?</h3>
          <p>They still need the details. If it’s urgent, tag them with a short summary and what decision you need. If it’s not urgent, email or drop the notes in the appropriate channel.</p>
          <h3>Isn’t it rude to skip a greeting?</h3>
          <p>You can say “Hi!”—just follow it immediately with your request. Consider it the digital equivalent of “Hi, can I borrow you for 2 minutes about the SOC report?”</p>
        </div>

        <div class="legal-footer">
          <p>Thanks for helping us keep Ylsoo courteous <em>and</em> efficient. Send context, save time, ship faster.</p>
          <div class="legal-links">
            <a href="/">Back to Home</a>
            <span>•</span>
            <a href="/contact">Contact us</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

